This is invalid:

    strcat(string, &amp;c);

The second parameter to `strcat` is expected to be a pointer to a null terminated string.  But instead you&#39;re passing the address of a single character.  As a result, `strcat` will read past the memory bounds of `c` looking for a byte with the value 0.  This invokes [undefined behavior](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Undefined_behavior).

Instead, keep track of the number of characters in `string` and copy the new character to the end.  Then when you&#39;re done, add a terminating null byte to make it a proper string.

    char c;
    char *string = malloc(1);
    string[0] = 0;
    int len = 0;

    do
    {
        c = fgetc(fptr);

        printf(&quot;CHAR read %c\n&quot;, c);

        if (c == &#39; &#39; || c == &#39;\r&#39; || c == &#39;\n&#39;)
        {
            //do something with the word()
            free(string);
            len = 0;
            string = malloc(1);
            string[0] = 0;
        } else {
            string[len++] = c;
            string = realloc(string, len + 1);
            string[len] = 0;
        }
    } // while !EOF

